\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Deconvolution of bulk RNA expression data using single-cell RNA sequencing (scRNA-seq) is important because it allows researchers to infer the cellular composition of bulk tissues or samples. Bulk RNA sequencing measures the average gene expression across all cells within a sample, and therefore cannot distinguish between different cell types or states.\
On the other hand, scRNA-seq enables researchers to identify and profile the transcriptome of individual cells, allowing for the characterization of cell types and their heterogeneity within a sample. By comparing bulk RNA expression data to scRNA-seq data from the same or similar tissues, researchers can use deconvolution algorithms to estimate the proportions of different cell types present in the bulk sample.\
This can be useful for a variety of applications, such as identifying changes in cellular composition in disease states, monitoring the effects of drug treatments on different cell types, and characterizing the immune response to infection. Additionally, deconvolution can be used to identify cell-type-specific gene expression signatures, which can help to identify potential therapeutic targets or biomarkers for disease.\
